<div id='main'>
	
	<%= render 'info/generic_title' %>
	
	
	<div id='strip4'>
		<div id='strip4_content'>
			<div id='graphic'>
				<% if !@average_sysbp.nil? %>
					<div id='average_bp'>
						<%= render :partial => 'average_bp', :locals => {:avsys => @average_sysbp, :avdia => @average_diabp, :bppos => @bp_position} %>
					</div>
					<div id='reading_counter'>
						<%= render :partial => 'reading_counter' %>
					</div>	
				<% end %>
			</div>
			<div id='text'>
				<% if bp_warning_message(@current_average_bp) %>
				<p id='warning_msg'><%= bp_warning_message(@current_average_bp) %></p>
			<% end %>
	
			<% if !bp_warning_message(@current_average_bp) %>
				<p><%= average_bp_message(@average_sysbp, @average_diabp) %></p>
			<% end %>
	
			<% if user_signed_in? %>
			<p>...However, to get a more accurate picture of what your blood pressure is like you need to take more readings like this <span class='bold'><%= time_left %></span>. This is because your blood pressure will vary from hour to hour, so one or two readings can be misleading. By taking more readings, you will get more accurate advice from us.</p>
			<% else %>
			<p>...Next you need to sign up to our free service. Then you’ll be able to use our simple site to measure your blood pressure over the next four days. We’ll do all the hard work for you. After four days, you’ll have the most accurate home blood pressure reading possible.</p>
			<p id='feature_2'>Sign up below to start measuring your blood pressure at home.</p>
			<p>Why do I need to measure my blood pressure over four days? <%= link_to 'Find out here...', info_path('when-should-i-measure-my-blood-pressure') %></p>
			<% end %>
			</div>

		</div>
	</div>
	
	<div id='strip5'>
		<div id='strip5_content'>
			<% if user_signed_in? %>
				<p id='return_notice'>Please come back to HomeBloodPressure.co.uk <span class='bold'><%= when_next_bp_reading(@current_average_bp.ampm) %></span> to take another pair of blood pressure readings.</p>
			<% else %>
				<%= render :partial => 'devise/registrations/new' %>
			<% end %>
		</div>
	</div>
		
</div>


